the stake for witchcraft at the age of 18 or 19. Her story has captured the imagination of many writers, and she is variously portrayed as a national and political hero, a model of apolitical straightforwardness and honesty, and a religious heroine. She was canonized in  1920 . More recent influences have included the American film actress  Joan Crawford  (  1908–77 , born  Lucille le Sueur ), the British actress  Joan Collins  (  b. 1933 ), the American comedienne  Joan Rivers  (  b. 1933 ), and the West Indian pop singer  Joan Armatrading  (  b. 1950 )."],"variants":[{"name":"John","meanings":["New Testament: ‘God is gracious’.  See  <b>John</b> ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":42,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs Joan Buckeley was born in 1507, in Burgate, Hampshire, England, United Kingdom. She had at least 1 daughter with William Buckeley. She lived in Bedford, Bedfordshire, England in 1514. She died in 1556, in Bedford, Bedfordshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 49."},"et":{"1507–1556":"1507–1556","1489–1571":"1489–1571","1520–1591":"1520–1591","1556":"1556","1489":"1489","about 1515":"umbes 1515","1520":"1520","1571":"1571","1591":"1591","1507":"1507","1549":"1549","Burgate, Hampshire, England":"Burgate, Hampshire, England","Bedford, Bedfordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Bedford, Bedfordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Burgate Northampton England":"Burgate, Hampshire, Inglis